Which congenital deformity is shown in the image?
questions.solution: Correct Answer (B) The image shows features consistent with Anencephaly (absence of a major portion of the brain, skull, and scalp) combined with Craniorachischisis. Craniorachischisis is the most severe form of neural tube defect, where anencephaly is accompanied by a contiguous open defect of the entire spine (rachischisis). The visual evidence in the image includes the clear features of anencephaly, and the extremely short/absent neck with the head appearing to sit directly on the trunk strongly suggests a severe and continuous spinal defect consistent with rachischisis. Therefore, this option provides the most comprehensive and accurate description of the extensive malformation depicted. Incorrect Options: Option (A) Anencephaly Explanation: While anencephaly is clearly present in the image, this option is incomplete. The image suggests a more extensive defect involving the spine, as indicated by the absent neck and overall posture. If craniorachischisis (which includes anencephaly) is present, then "Anencephaly" alone does not capture the full scope of the deformity. Option (C) Meningomyelocele, Anencephaly Explanation: A meningomyelocele is a specific type of spina bifida where the spinal cord and meninges protrude through an opening, typically forming a sac-like structure. While an individual could have both anencephaly and a separate meningomyelocele, the term craniorachischisis describes a continuous, open defect of the brain and entire spinal cord. The image is more suggestive of this continuous, globally open neural tube defect rather than a distinct, localized meningomyelocele sac in addition to the anencephaly. Option (D) Spina bifida occulta, Anencephaly Explanation: Spina bifida occulta is the mildest form of spina bifida, characterized by a small, hidden gap in one or more vertebrae, usually without protrusion of neural tissue and often asymptomatic. This diagnosis is inconsistent with the severe and open spinal defect implied by the image, especially when associated with anencephaly. The visible malformations suggest a far more severe spinal condition than spina bifida occulta.

Patient presents with the numbness, tingling & Parasthesia of the lateral 3 & ½ Fingers including base of thumb. Which of the following is most likely involved in this patient?
questions.solution: Correct Answer (A) Explanation: The Median Nerve is most likely involved in this patient. The median nerve provides sensory innervation to the palmar aspect of the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and the lateral (radial) half of the ring finger. It also typically supplies sensation to the nail beds of these fingers. Numbness, tingling, and paresthesia in this specific distribution, often referred to as the "lateral 3 & ½ fingers," including involvement of the base of the thumb (thenar eminence area, also innervated by the median nerve), is characteristic of median nerve neuropathy, commonly seen in conditions like Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. Incorrect Options: Option (B) Radial N. Explanation: The Radial Nerve primarily provides sensation to the posterior aspect of the arm and forearm, and the dorsal (back) surface of the hand, including the thumb, index, middle, and lateral half of the ring finger up to the proximal interphalangeal or distal interphalangeal joints, but typically not the fingertips on the palmar side. While it innervates parts of the thumb and lateral fingers, the described pattern, especially if involving the palmar aspect and fingertips, points more strongly to the median nerve. Option (C) Ulnar N. Explanation: The Ulnar Nerve supplies sensation to the little finger (5th digit) and the medial (ulnar) half of the ring finger (4th digit), as well as the corresponding medial aspect of the palm and dorsum of the hand. This distribution is distinct from the lateral 3 & ½ fingers described. Option (D) PIN (Posterior Interosseous Nerve) Explanation: The Posterior Interosseous Nerve (PIN) is a deep motor branch of the radial nerve. It innervates muscles in the forearm responsible for finger and thumb extension. Lesions of the PIN typically cause weakness in these movements (e.g., finger drop) and do not cause direct cutaneous sensory loss in the fingers like numbness or tingling. Sensory symptoms in the radial nerve distribution would typically involve the superficial radial nerve, not the PIN.

questions.text: Patient presents with the numbness, tingling & Parasthesia of the lateral 3 & ½ Fingers including base of thumb (Dorsum). Which of the following is most likely involved in this patient?
questions.solution: Correct Answer (B) Explanation: The Radial Nerve, specifically its superficial sensory branch, is most likely involved in this patient. The superficial radial nerve provides cutaneous sensation to the dorsum (back) of the hand on the radial side. This includes the dorsal aspect of the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and the lateral (radial) half of the ring finger, typically up to the level of the distal interphalangeal joints or nail beds. The description of numbness, tingling, and paresthesia in the "lateral 3 & ½ Fingers including base of thumb (Dorsum)" precisely matches this distribution. Incorrect Options: Option (A) Median N. Explanation: The Median Nerve primarily supplies sensation to the palmar aspect of the lateral 3 & ½ fingers and the dorsal aspects of their fingertips (distal phalanges). It does not innervate the majority of the dorsum of these fingers or the dorsal base of the thumb. Option (C) Ulnar N. Explanation: The Ulnar Nerve supplies sensation to the little finger, the medial (ulnar) half of the ring finger, and the corresponding medial aspect of both the palm and dorsum of the hand. This distribution is different from the lateral 3 & ½ fingers described. Option (D) PIN (Posterior Interosseous Nerve) Explanation: The Posterior Interosseous Nerve (PIN) is a deep motor branch of the radial nerve. It is responsible for innervating muscles that extend the fingers and thumb. A lesion of the PIN typically causes motor weakness (e.g., finger drop) and does not cause cutaneous sensory loss like numbness or tingling in the fingers. Sensory symptoms related to the radial nerve territory are mediated by its superficial sensory branches.
